{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476953"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13998"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13998"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.79,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115184"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6632"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13998"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97192"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"731"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"2555"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48791"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115184"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with an episode of collapse that spontaneously resolved. Her parents report that she was running around with friends when she suddenly fainted. This is the first time this has occurred, although her parents report that sometimes she has episodes of her heart beating very fast. There is no family history of unexplained syncope or sudden cardiac death. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. An ECG is performed, as shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate cardioversion","Oral amiodarone","Referral to a paediatric cardiologist","Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator","Digoxin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG findings described are characteristic of Wolff-Parkinson-White (WPW) syndrome. The classic ECG features of WPW include a short PR interval (less than 120 ms), a widened QRS complex (greater than 120 ms), and the presence of delta waves. Delta waves are best seen in leads V1-V4 as a slurred upstroke at the beginning of the QRS complex. These findings represent pre-excitation of the ventricles via an accessory pathway. ST changes, as seen in this ECG, are also common. The most appropriate next step in management for this child is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to a paediatric cardiologist\u003C/strong\u003E. A specialist evaluation is crucial to confirm the diagnosis, assess the risk of sudden cardiac death, and determine the most appropriate long-term management strategy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case as the patient is currently stable and not in an acute arrhythmia. Cardioversion would only be necessary if the patient presented with a life-threatening tachyarrhythmia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used as first-line treatment for WPW in children due to its potential long-term side effects. Beta-blockers are often preferred as initial pharmacological management if medication is deemed necessary by the cardiologist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eimplantable cardioverter-defibrillator\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overly aggressive approach at this stage. This intervention is usually reserved for patients with WPW who have survived a cardiac arrest or those deemed at very high risk of sudden cardiac death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in WPW as it can potentially increase conduction through the accessory pathway, potentially precipitating dangerous arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe paediatric cardiologist will likely perform further investigations, such as an echocardiogram and possibly an electrophysiology study. They may recommend lifestyle modifications, such as avoiding triggers like caffeine or excessive exercise. Depending on the frequency and severity of symptoms, they might suggest pharmacological management (often with beta-blockers) or catheter ablation of the accessory pathway. The management approach will be tailored to the individual patient, considering factors such as age, frequency of symptoms, and risk stratification.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ECG characteristics of Wolff-Parkinson-White (WPW) syndrome are a short PR interval, widened QRS, and delta waves (seen most clearly in V1-V4 as an up-sloping at the beginning of the initial QRS wave).","Management of WPW syndrome in children includes referral to a paediatric cardiologist, avoidance of triggers, and consideration of catheter ablation.","Beta-blockers are often used as first-line pharmacological treatment for symptomatic WPW in children."],"references":["The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne Clinical Practice Guidelines [Internet]. 2020 [updated 2020 Aug; cited 2020 Feb 15]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/WolffParkinsonWhite_Syndrome/","Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m I, \u00d6zer S, Karag\u00f6z T, \u015eahin M, \u00d6zkutlu S, Alehan D, \u00c7eliker A. Clinical and electrophysiological evaluation of pediatric Wolff-Parkinson-White patients. Anatolian journal of cardiology. 2015 Jun;15(6):485","Life in the Fast Lane [Internet]. 2020 [updated 2021 Feb 7; cited 2020 Feb 15]. Available from: https://litfl.com/hypertrophic-cardiomyopathy-hcm-ecg-library/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97192"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13998"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22134"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22134"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e4RWJReoNsO3auA6rlncGThKB7wgVd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e4RWJReoNsO3auA6rlncGThKB7wgVd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":562,"height":335}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97192"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T09:18:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T09:19:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6632"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115184"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9